(299, 1, '2023-04-14 20:18:07', '2023-04-14 20:18:07', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>WordPress supports the pagination function (<strong>posts_nav_link()</strong>) that you can insert just before or after the main loop within the&nbsp;<strong>index.php</strong>&nbsp;file of your theme. Here’s a simplified example of what the code looks like:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&lt;?php <strong>if</strong> ( have_posts() ) : ?&gt;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&lt;!-- Add the pagination functions here. →</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>posts_nav_link()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&lt;!-- Start <strong>of</strong> the main loop. --&gt;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&lt;?php <strong>while</strong> ( have_posts() ) : the_post(); ?&gt;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&lt;!-- the rest <strong>of</strong> your theme\'s main loop --&gt;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&lt;?php endwhile; ?&gt;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&lt;!-- End of the main loop --&gt;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&lt;!-- Or add the pagination functions here. --&gt;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&lt;div class=\"nav-previous alignleft\"&gt;&lt;?php previous_posts_link( \'Older posts\' ); ?&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&lt;div class=\"nav-next alignright\"&gt;&lt;?php next_posts_link( \'Newer posts\' ); ?&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&lt;?php else : ?&gt;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&lt;p&gt;&lt;?php _e(\'Sorry, no posts matched your criteria.\'); ?&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&lt;?php endif; ?&gt;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We recommend using a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.hostinger.in/tutorials/how-to-create-wordpress-child-theme\">child theme</a>&nbsp;to make this modification instead of implementing it directly in the parent theme. A child theme inherits all of its parent theme’s functionality, style, and features, therefore allowing you to keep the changes made after any theme updates.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"h-2-adding-css-code-to-edit-the-pagination\">2. Adding CSS Code to Edit the Pagination</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Another way to implement pagination is to add&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.hostinger.in/tutorials/what-is-html\">HTML</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.hostinger.in/tutorials/what-is-css\">CSS</a>&nbsp;code to your active theme. Many custom CSS code snippets you can use are available on web development platforms like&nbsp;<a href=\"https://codepen.io/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">CodePen</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The following is a custom pagination function designed by&nbsp;<a href=\"https://codepen.io/arefeh_htmi/pen/ExKewzW\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Arefeh Hatami</a>. It utilizes HTML and CSS to create a simple page number navigation bar. If you decide to implement this snippet in your WordPress site, feel free to experiment with different styles as needed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":46156,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://www.hostinger.in/tutorials/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2022/02/navigation-bar.png\"><img src=\"https://www.hostinger.in/tutorials/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2022/02/navigation-bar.png\" alt=\"A simple page navigation bar created using HTML and CSS by Arefeh Hatami.\" class=\"wp-image-46156\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"h-3-managing-content-per-page\">3. Managing Content per Page</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Unlike the previous methods, this one doesn’t involve coding. Instead, you only need to have access to the WordPress admin dashboard.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Navigate to&nbsp;<strong>Settings&nbsp;</strong>-&gt;&nbsp;<strong>Reading&nbsp;</strong>from the WordPress dashboard.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Edit the&nbsp;<strong>Blog pages show at most</strong>&nbsp;value.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->', 'Adjusting the PHP Code in the functions.php File', 'We recommend using a child theme to make this modification instead of implementing it directly in the parent theme. A child theme inherits all of its parent theme’s functionality, style, and features, therefore allowing you to keep the changes made after any theme updates.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'adjusting-the-php-code-in-the-functions-php-file', '', '', '2023-04-14 20:18:07', '2023-04-14 20:18:07', '', 0, 'http://localhost/learncustom/?p=299', 0, 'post', '', 0),
